            "command": "insert_content",
            "content": "\n\n## Codified LLM rules for mission-friction analysis\n\nMission sessions have an orchestrator, workers, handoffs, features, validation criteria, and architecture notes. Evaluate the mission as a whole: did coordination problems waste time, hide failures, or let the mission drift away from its contract?\n\nReport mission friction when you see concrete impact such as:\n\n- **Repeated worker handoff failures with the same unresolved cause.** Example: a validator worker fails twice with `factoryd appears to be unavailable`, the orchestrator keeps restarting workers for the same milestone, and the mission cannot continue until the user restarts Droid. This is friction because coordination stalled and the same failure recurred without recovery. Do not report a single daemon crash that is immediately resumed and completed.\n- **The same feature is worked on more than four times without a new reason each time.** Example: a mission shows `keychain-service` or a validator feature started, failed, or restarted many times with repeated `process exited unexpectedly` or timeout reasons. This is friction if the repeated attempts are retrying the same work or same failure. It is not friction when repeated validators are distinct review rounds over new commits with new blockers and clear progress.\n- **Validation criteria are weakened or overwritten to fit the implementation.** Example: a worker says a validation item cannot satisfy `checkout PR head SHA`, then the orchestrator marks the assertion as `builds include PR branch code via merge commit` and later treats it as passed without explicit user approval. This is high-confidence friction because the mission contract changed after implementation. In contrast, a failed assertion that remains failed, gets a fix feature, and passes on rerun is healthy mission behavior.\n- **Handoff items are dismissed instead of addressed.** Example: the same checkout-ref limitation appears in worker handoff, scrutiny findings, and dismissal logs; the orchestrator dismisses it as already addressed while the underlying mismatch remains. This is friction when dismissal prevents an actionable blocker or follow-up from being handled. It is not friction when the dismissal explicitly documents that an item is pre-existing, out of scope, or superseded and the later mission evidence supports that decision.\n- **Architecture decisions are ignored.** Example: an architecture note says a reusable workflow is off-limits or a design path is canonical, but workers solve the task by contradicting that plan or changing validation to match the deviation. This is weaker evidence on its own; report it only when the drift causes rework, failed validation, repeated handoffs, or user-visible uncertainty.\n\nPrefer findings that cite both the problematic event and the later impact, such as the original failed handoff plus the repeated restart, dismissal, validation-state change, or follow-up fix feature.\n\n### Negative examples: do not count as mission friction\n\n- A single worker/daemon failure that is immediately resumed and completed without repeated retries.\n- A validator feature run multiple times because each run reviews a new commit or a newly fixed blocker.\n- A validation failure that stays failed, leads to a dedicated fix feature, then passes on rerun.\n- A handoff item dismissed as pre-existing, out of scope, or superseded when later evidence supports that dismissal.\n- Architecture drift mentioned in isolation with no rework, failed validation, repeated handoffs, or user-visible uncertainty.\n",
